nean and Cuban artists such as Carlos Estévez, León Ferrari, Mirta Kupferminc, Nicolás Menza, and Estela Pereda. This philosophical exploration of how artists have interpreted literature contributes to both aesthetics and hermeneutics, makes new inroads into the understanding of Borges's work, and introduces readers to two of the most vibrant artistic currents today. Color images of the artworks discussed are included.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArt -- Philosophy. 0aArt and literature. 0aArtxPhilosophy. 0aBorges, Jorge Luis, -- 1899-1986 -- Illustrations. 0aBorges, Jorge Luis, -- 1899-1986 -- Themes, motives. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Art Theory. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438441795423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438441795/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles